RADIKANT-MESSAGEPACK-C - PERFORMANCE REVIEW
=============================================

SCOPE
-----
Reviewed encoder.c, decoder.c, zone.c, skip.c, stream.c, object.c
(~2060 LOC total). Looking for structural inefficiencies only -
not micro-optimizations.

FINDING #1 (real, actionable)
------------------------------
Location : decoder.c, all four map-decode sites
           (fixmap, MAP16, MAP32 - pattern duplicated 3x)

Issue    : Map entries are allocated as two SEPARATE zone
           allocations per entry, instead of stored by value.

    out_obj->via.map.ptr[i].key =
        (mp_object_t*) mp_zone_alloc(zone, sizeof(mp_object_t));
    out_obj->via.map.ptr[i].val =
        (mp_object_t*) mp_zone_alloc(zone, sizeof(mp_object_t));

  Compare to array decoding, which allocates the whole element
  block in ONE call:

    out_obj->via.array.ptr =
        mp_zone_alloc(zone, sizeof(mp_object_t) * len);

  For a map with N entries:
    - 1 alloc for the mp_object_kv_t array   (correct, matches array)
    - 2N additional small zone_alloc calls   (unnecessary)

  Root cause: mp_object_kv_t stores key/val as POINTERS

    typedef struct {
        mp_object_t* key;
        mp_object_t* val;
    } mp_object_kv_t;

  instead of embedding them by value:

    typedef struct {
        mp_object_t key;
        mp_object_t val;
    } mp_object_kv_t;

IMPACT
------
  - ~3x more zone_alloc calls than structurally necessary for
    map-heavy payloads (common case: nested JSON-like objects).
  - Extra pointer indirection paid on every READ after decode too
    (ptr[i].key->via... vs a flat ptr[i].key.via...), not just
    during parsing.
  - Arrays don't have this problem - only maps.

FIX
---
  Change mp_object_kv_t to hold key/val by value, decode directly
  into ptr[i].key / ptr[i].val the same way array elements are
  decoded directly into ptr[i]. Removes 2N allocations and one
  pointer hop per access.

OTHER AREAS CHECKED - NO REAL BOTTLENECK FOUND
------------------------------------------------
  - encoder.c: single mp_encode_bytes() per primitive, matches
    normal streaming-encoder design, nothing wasteful.
  - stream.c dynamic write buffer: capacity doubling loop is
    correct amortized O(1) growth, no issue.
  - zone.c bump allocator: leftover space in an exhausted chunk
    is abandoned rather than reused - this is a known tradeoff
    of arena allocators (same as msgpack-c), not a bug or a
    meaningful bottleneck under normal chunk sizing.
  - decoder.c byte-at-a-time header reads: inherent to the
    streaming/vtable stream design, not fixable without changing
    the whole I/O model - not "obvious" in the sense asked for.

BOTTOM LINE
-----------
One real finding: map decoding does ~3x the allocation work
arrays do, for no structural reason. Everything else in the hot
path (recursion, stream reads, encoding) already does the
minimal necessary work.